nodes.title: Watermark Detection
widgets_values:
If you see a white mask in the Watermark Mask node, then something was detected. 

Detection Threshold: Raise or lower the detection threshold as needed. (Yes, even down to 0.00001). Lowering it makes it more sensitive. 1 is the highest and basically makes it detect nothing.

Disclaimer: this does not always detect watermarks, but it does work most of the time. Some generated watermarks, text, etc., just fail to get detected no matter what.

There is a CLIPSeg method of doing this using way less nodes, but I have run into issues with that method and will stick with what works for me. (Gemini agrees that the CLIPSeg method has issues).

BBOX Detector (SEGS): 

You can adjust the prompts in this node to whatever you want. I think the default is "all".

nodes.title: Epsilon Scaling Reference (ChatGPT)
widgets_values:
#  Epsilon Scaling  Integration Reference

---

###  What Epsilon Scaling Actually Does
Epsilon Scaling adjusts the *magnitude of noise scaling* during sampling.  
It modifies how aggressively each step interprets the diffusion noise amplitude   
think of it as **micro-contrast control at the sampler level**.

| scaling_factor Range | Behavior |
|----------------------|-----------|
| **1.0011.006** | Subtle refinement, smoother gradients |
| **1.0071.012** | Balanced sharpness boost, clean texture |
| **1.0131.020** | Aggressive microcontrast, risk of halos / oversharp edges |


---

###  Recommended scaling_factor Values (per Stage)

| Stage | scaling_factor | Purpose |
|--------|----------------|----------|
| **Base Sampler** | **1.0071.010** | Adds crispness to fine edges and fabric |
| **USDU #1** | **1.0051.008** | Maintains texture coherence without grain |
| **USDU #2** | **1.0021.004** | Smooth tonal refinement, avoids halos |
| **FaceDetailer (Face)** | **1.0031.005** | Optional subtle sharpening |
| **FaceDetailer (Hands / Eyes)** | **1.0011.002** | Gentle microtexture boost if needed |

 Start with Base + USDU #1 only, then expand if stable.

---

###  Visual Impact by Stage

| Stage | Effect of Epsilon Scaling | If Too High |
|--------|---------------------------|--------------|
| **Base** | Sharper edges, cleaner structure | Grain or crispy outlines |
| **USDU #1** | Adds clarity across tiles | Edge aliasing / double texture |
| **USDU #2** | Smooth refinement | Metallic shine / false highlights |
| **FaceDetailer** | Enhances microtexture | Hard shadows / overdefinition |

---

###  Summary Recommendations

- Keep Epsilon Scaling active on **Base Sampler**, **USDU #1**, and optionally **FaceDetailer**.  
- Use **lower values (1.004)** on **USDU #2** to avoid shine or extra texture.  
- Start low and increase gradually  *you can always add detail, but cant remove halos later*.  
- If using **Normal scheduler**, stay  **1.008** (it already increases contrast).  
- If using **Karras**, you can safely go up to **1.0101.012** for extra crispness.  

---

 *Epsilon Scaling acts like a precision sharpening dial  small values yield big control when combined with CFG Zero Star.*

nodes.title: Global Sampler and Global Seed
widgets_values:
### Global Seed will override all seed related settings on the other nodes in the workflow.

### Global Sampler will override the sampler and scheduler settings on the other nodes in the workflow. 

### Selecting a Sampler/Scheduler not compatible with all nodes will result in an error.

## Parameter Info:

https://github.com/Coyote-A/ultimate-upscale-for-automatic1111/wiki/FAQ#parameters-descriptions

### Tips based on my experience and what various AI have explained:

You can drop the tile_padding to a lower number like 128 and USDU will work faster, but increases the chance of weird stuff happening. The bigger the tile_padding, the more USDU "looks" at while working.

## FYI: Not all samplers/schedulers play nice with USDU.

## Upscale Model:

You can use whatever you prefer. Some upscale models seem to have issues with USDU, so YMMV.

### If you want the one I am using, you can get it here:

https://huggingface.co/Kim2091/UltraSharpV2/tree/main

nodes.title: Power Lora Loader (ChatGPT)
widgets_values:
#  Power Lora Loader (rgthree)

The **Power Lora Loader** is an advanced node from **rgthrees ComfyUI extensions** that improves on the default Lora loader with extra tools for browsing, previewing, and managing Loras. Its particularly useful if you work with models downloaded from **Civitai** or keep a large collection of Loras with metadata.

---

##  Basic Functionality
- **Loads LoRAs** (Low-Rank Adapters) into a model pipeline, just like the normal `LoraLoader` node.
- Lets you **stack multiple LoRAs**, reorder them, and control their individual strengths.
- Supports **drag-and-drop loading** from the ComfyUI file browser.

---

##  Right-Click Menu Features
Right-click on any loaded LoRA inside the node to open its context menu.

###  Show Info
- **Fetch info from civitai** from the LoRAs embedded info or directly from its `model.json` or `civitai.info` file (if available).
- Shows:
  - Model Name
  - Version
  - Author
  - Trained Base Model
  - Civitai URL
  - Description (short)
  - Suggested Trigger Words
- If the `.safetensors` file has embedded metadata (Civitai automatically includes it), Power Lora Loader reads it locally  **no internet needed**.

---

##  Trigger Word Tools

###  Trained Words
If the lora has any trigger words/trained words. They will be listed after fetching the info from civitai.
- There will be a listing of all known **trigger phrases** or **keywords** associated with that LoRA.
- You can **click on a trigger** to copy it directly to your clipboard.
- Useful for pasting into your prompt, prompt node, or **Markdown Note node**.
  
>  You can also **Ctrl+Click** or **Shift+Click** multiple trigger words to copy them together, separated by commas.

---

##  Image Previews
After fetching the info from civitai, it will also display sample images toward the bottom of the popup window.

If the LoRA has **multiple preview images**, you can cycle through them (small arrows appear when more than one image is found).

---

##  Multi-LoRA Controls
- Add multiple LoRAs to the same node with the  button.
- Adjust **strength (weight)** sliders per LoRA.
- Reorder LoRAs with drag handles.
- Toggle individual LoRAs on/off with checkboxes.

---

# Detailer (SEGS)
---
## This detailer will take all detections and run them at once. Theoretically, if doing this for eyes, this should perform better than using the normal FaceDetailer node and doing them individually and won't include half of the face like some "paired eyes" models. The mask preview node to the left will show what was detected and being detailed. You may need to bump up the guide_size and max_size if there are multiple sets of eyes. When using this for eyes: I run this at two cycles, but you do you.
